messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

[
  {
    "path": null,
    "handler": "App\\Http\\Controllers\\CommentController@store",
    "implementationPresentInFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathExtractedFromLiteral": false,
    "pathDerivedFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isRestful": true,
    "isTest": false
  },
  {
    "path": null,
    "handler": "App\\Http\\Controllers\\CommentController@destroy",
    "implementationPresentInFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathExtractedFromLiteral": false,
    "pathDerivedFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isRestful": true,
    "isTest": false
  }
]

Explanation:

- No HTTP route paths (literal strings like '/comments' or '/posts/{id}') are present in this source file. The file only defines the controller class and its methods (store and destroy); it does not declare route definitions. Because of that, the "path" field is set to null for both entries (per your instruction to set path to null when it cannot be determined).
- The two entries correspond to the controller methods implemented in this file:
  - store(CommentsRequest $request)
  - destroy(Comment $comment)
  Both method implementations are present in the same file, so implementationPresentInFile is true.
- These controller methods are standard RESTful action names (store → create resource, destroy → delete resource), so I marked isRestful true. However, no routing literal or resource-route declaration is present here, so I did not derive any concrete path strings from naming conventions (pathDerivedFromNamingConvention is false) — we are not inferring routes from external route files.
- pathExtractedFromLiteral is false because there are no route path literals in this file. pathIsPrefix is false because there is no path to classify as a prefix.
- isTest is false since these methods are part of application controllers, not test code.

If you provide the routes file(s) (for example routes/web.php or routes/api.php) or any route registration code that references this controller, I can extract concrete paths (e.g., POST /comments for store, DELETE /comments/{comment} for destroy) and populate the path fields and the path-derived-from-convention flag accordingly.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
path.title: Path

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.
handler_in_same_file.title: Handler In Same File

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.
path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix

path_from_string_literal.description: Whether the path string is extracted from a literal string defined in the source code.
path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.
path_from_naming_convention.title: Path From Naming Convention

is_restful_api.description: Whether the API entry is for a RESTful API, rather than other types of APIs.
